\section{Public-health and environmental relevance}{

Climate normals serve as the \strong{climatological baseline} against which
observed exposures are compared in epidemiological studies:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Heat-health}: temperature normals reveal chronically hot
municipalities for heat-wave attribution and heat-related mortality studies.
\item \strong{Precipitation extremes}: wet-day and dry-spell normals support
flood and drought exposure assessments linked to diarrhoeal disease,
leptospirosis, and waterborne outbreaks.
\item \strong{Vector-borne diseases}: humidity and temperature normals define
the climatic envelope of \emph{Aedes} mosquito habitat, informing dengue,
chikungunya and Zika risk mapping.
\item \strong{Relative-risk baselines}: DLNM models built with
\code{\link[=sus_mod_dlnm]{sus_mod_dlnm()}} require a reference exposure; normals provide the
station-level climatological mean for that reference.
\item \strong{Vulnerability indices}: combined with \code{\link[=sus_mod_vulnerability_index]{sus_mod_vulnerability_index()}},
normals quantify chronic exposure as an IPCC \emph{hazard} pillar component.
}
